78l.title: Asymptotic Notation
78l.clickbait: Asymptotic notation seeks to capture the behavior of functions as its input(s) become extreme.  It is most widely used in Computer Science and Numerical Approximation.
78l.text:
Asymptotic Notation (BachmannLandau notation) is a notation for comparing the behavior of functions at extreme values  both very large, and very small.  This is a convenient way to compare the performance of algorithms on large inputs, as well as the accuracy of approximations.  This page will focus on the values at very large values, which is useful for analyzing the behavior of algorithms, rather than very minute values.

## Asymptotic Behavior ##

The asymptotic behavior of a function is its behavior as its input grows large.

![](http://i.imgur.com/Hpaud68.png)

For example, as x grows large, the three functions above all start to take on the same asymptotic behavior.  Asymptotic notation gives a way to express the relationship between two functions' asymptotic behaviors.

## Definition of Little-Oh ##

Suppose we have two functions f(x) and g(x), and the statement $f(x) = o(g(x))$ is true (read this as "f is big oh of g").  Formally, this means

$$\forall_c \exists_n \text{ such that } \forall_{x>n} f(x) \leq c \cdot g(x)$$

In other words, no matter how small we scale $g(x)$, it will eventually overtake $f(x)$.  Equivalently, $f(x) = o(g(x))$ if (and only if)

$$\lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = 0$$.

### A Note on Notation ###

While the standard notation uses an equal sign (i.e. $f(x) = o(g(x))$), a more precise notation might be $f(c) \in o(g(x))$, where $o(g(x))$ is the set of functions that are, in some sense, smaller than $g(x)$ (asymptotically).  Nonetheless, using an equal sign is customary, and is the notation that will be used here.

## Properties of Little-Oh ##

 1. $f(x) = o(f(x))$ is always false
 2. $f(x) = o(g(x))\ \ \implies\ \ g(x) \neq o(f(x))$
 3. $f(x) = o(g(x)) \text{ and } g(x) = o(h(x))\ \ \implies\ \ f(x)= o(h(x))$
 4. $f(x) = o(g(x))\ \ \implies\ \ c + f(x) = o(g(x))$
 5. $f(x) = o(g(x))\ \ \implies\ \ c \cdot f(x) = o(g(x))$
 6. $f(x) = o(g(x))\ \ \iff\ \ \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = 0$

The first three properties are essentially the same properties required of a strict ordering, which means that this notation gives us a way to order functions by how quickly the grow, as x approaches infinity (see the "Common Functions" section)

The 4th and 5th properties show that asymptotic notation does not care about adding or multiplying by constants.  This is useful in computer science, where constant factors may vary by hardware, and it is desirable to compare algorithms independent of the hardware that is running it.

The last property suggests a powerful way of determining the asymptotic behavior of two functions  in fact, combined with [L'Hpital's Rule](http://mathworld.wolfram.com/LHospitalsRule.html), it is often all one needs.

## Example ##

### Example 1 ###

Consider $f(x) = 200x + 10000$ and $g(x) = x^2$.  Prove that $f(x) = o(g(x))$.

![](http://i.imgur.com/TZF5hQn.png)

$$\lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{200x + 10000}{x^2}$$

Though this limit doesn't seem particularly approachable, L'Hpital's Rule makes short work of it:

$$\lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{200x + 10000}{x^2} = \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{200}{2x} = 0$$

Therefore, by property 7, $f(x) = o(g(x))$.

### Example 2 ###

Let $f(x) = 20x^2 - 10x + 5$ and $g(x) = 2x^3 - x^2 + 10$.  Again, we will use property 7, combined with L'Hpital's Rule:

$$\lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{20x^2 - 10x + 5}{2x^3 - x^2 + 10} = \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{40x - 10}{6x^2 - 2x}$$

Unlike the previous example, applying L'Hpital's Rule doesn't seem to have reduced the fraction to an easily evaluable limit.  Fortunately, we are welcome to apply L'Hpital's Rule as many times as we like, without changing the value of the limit.

$$= \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{40}{12x} = \lim{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{0}{12} = 0$$

Therefore $f(x) = o(g(x))$.

## Common Functions ##

Functions that are frequently seen while analyzing algorithms are of particular use and interest.  Because little-Oh notation suggests a strict ordering, the following functions are listed from smallest to largest, asymptotically.

 1. $f(x) = c$
 2. $f(x) = log(log(x))$
 3. $f(x) = log(x)$
 4. $f(x) = x$
 5. $f(x) = x \cdot log(x)$
 6. $f(x) = x^{1+\epsilon}$, $0 < \epsilon < 1$
 7. $f(x) = x^2$
 8. $f(x) = x^3$
 9. $f(x) = x^4$
 10. ...
 11. $f(x) = e^x$
 12. $f(x) = x!$
